Why Monte Carlo simulation matters

Traditional retirement calculators give you one number based on average returns: "Your portfolio grows at 8% per year." But real markets don't move in straight lines.

Markets swing between crashes and rallies. The sequence of those returns matters enormously ‚Äî retiring right before a crash produces a radically different outcome than retiring at a peak.

Monte Carlo simulation runs your plan through thousands of possible scenarios to show the full range ‚Äî from best case to worst case.

Case Study ¬∑ Singapore

Nelson & Family ‚Äî "Can we retire at 55?"

A Singaporean accounting professional stress-tests his retirement plan against 10,000 market scenarios. The result: a hidden risk traditional calculators completely miss.

üá∏üá¨ Singaporeüìä Balanced (50/50)üè† CPF Life + Rental
Profile

Nelson Tan, 55 ‚Äî Married, Singapore

Nelson is an accounting professional considering immediate retirement. He and his wife have built a diversified set of income sources over the years.

Assets & Income

What Nelson has to work with

  • Home: Fully-owned HDB flat (primary residence).
  • Investment Property: A partially-paid private shoebox apartment. Provides $18,000/year after-tax income, growing with inflation (2.5% p.a.).
  • Pension: CPF Life set aside. Will pay $12,000/year starting at age 65.
  • Portfolio: $450,000 nest egg in a balanced portfolio (50% Global Equities / 50% Local Bonds).
The Big Question
Can Nelson retire now with annual living expenses of $48,000 ($4,000 per month)?
Traditional Forecast

The linear answer: "Yes, comfortably"

Using steady, risk-free returns, Nelson's assets would fund a comfortable retirement until he turns 85.

This looks great on paper. A smooth curve showing money lasting 30 years. Most retirement calculators stop here.
Monte Carlo Simulation

The RetireSIM reality: a hidden 20% risk

When we model thousands of realistic market scenarios with ups and downs, a crucial risk emerges.

‚ö† Critical Finding
20% chance the portfolio is exhausted up to 9 years early

In 1 out of 5 possible market scenarios, Nelson could run out of money by age 76 instead of 85.

What drives this risk? Sequence-of-returns risk. If a major crash occurs in the first 5‚Äì10 years of retirement, Nelson is forced to sell at depressed prices, permanently reducing his portfolio's recovery potential.

Case Study ¬∑ Global / FIRE

Emma Clark ‚Äî chasing FIRE by 45

A freelance developer with a 90/10 equity-heavy portfolio and aggressive savings rate. Monte Carlo shows her $1.5M target is a coin flip ‚Äî not a certainty.

üåç Digital Nomadüìä Aggressive (90/10)üéØ $1.5M Target
Profile

Emma Clark, 33 ‚Äî Single, Digital Nomad

Emma is a FIRE enthusiast who works remotely as a freelance software developer, leveraging geo-arbitrage to minimize expenses while traveling through Southeast Asia and Europe.

The Aggressive Plan

Emma's FIRE strategy

  • Current Portfolio: $350,000 in a globally diversified, equity-heavy portfolio (90% Global Equities / 10% Bonds).
  • Savings Rate: Puts aside $35,000 annually from her high freelance income.
  • FIRE Target: Accumulate $1.5 million by age 45 (12 years) to fund a permanently sustainable retirement.
The Core Question
Can her savings rate and aggressive strategy realistically hit $1.5M in 12 years? What is the probability of success?
Traditional Forecast

The linear answer: "Right on schedule"

Assuming a steady 8% annual return, her portfolio would surpass $1.5M just before age 45.

Typical FIRE calculators show this. A smooth upward curve hitting your target on schedule. But is it realistic?
Monte Carlo Simulation

The RetireSIM reality: a coin flip, not a certainty

When we stress-test against thousands of scenarios ‚Äî bear markets, sequence risk, variable inflation ‚Äî the picture changes dramatically.

‚ö† Sobering Reality
Only 50% probability of reaching her goal by 45

It's a coin flip ‚Äî half of market scenarios get her to $1.5M on time, half don't.

‚úï Worst Case Scenarios
In 10% of scenarios, she falls short by $600,000+

A major bear market during her late 30s or early 40s could delay her FIRE date by 5‚Äì7 years.

Why such high variance? Her 90/10 allocation amplifies both gains and losses. A prolonged downturn in her early 40s ‚Äî when her portfolio is largest ‚Äî could substantially delay her target.

Discover the full analysis: Explore outcomes, crash impact, and levers like savings rate and allocation in the Monte Carlo tab.
